FETSORN
So I was looking for the origins of video games that I like. It came down to crawlers and arpgs in 90s, text adventures in the 80s, and then to games written in [TUTOR](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TUTOR#Structure_of_a_TUTOR_lesson) for the [PLATO](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PLATO_(computer_system)) system.

FETSORN
there were some languages based on TUTOR - [cT](https://vpython.org/contents/cTsource/cToverview.html), vPython, [GlowScript](https://www.glowscript.org/#/user/GlowScriptDemos/folder/Examples/)

FETSORN
But it's easy enough to run an emulator of a PLATO system and work with TUTOR directly

FETSORN
VERY IMPORTANT! This is the "The TUTOR language" [book](https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED124149) that has everything on the language

FETSORN
Early on I found a [user guide](http://www.bitsavers.org/pdf/cdc/plato/97405900C_PLATO_Users_Guide_Apr81.pdf) that seemed outdated, and a [wiki](https://emulation.gametechwiki.com/index.php/PLATO_Computer_System)

FETSORN
There's a [cyber1](https://www.cyber1.org/faq.asp) service that runs a PLATO CYBIS network. There's also IRATA [network](https://irata.online/users/confirmation)

FETSORN
I [looked](https://github.com/search?q=plato+emulator) for a way to run my own CYBIS. Some failed attempts: [platoterm99](https://github.com/tschak909/platoterm99), [platoterm-plan9](https://github.com/tschak909/platoterm-plan9).

FETSORN
after failures I tried to figure out which emulators I would actually need to assemble the network myself.

FETSORN
[StackExchange: Did communication between a PLATO terminal and mainframe use pushes?](https://retrocomputing.stackexchange.com/questions/18136/did-communication-between-a-plato-terminal-and-mainframe-use-pushes).

FETSORN
[Bradrico Rigg: Run your own mainframe using Hercules mainframe emulator and MVS 3.8j tk4](https://bradricorigg.medium.com/run-your-own-mainframe-using-hercules-mainframe-emulator-and-mvs-3-8j-tk4-55fa7c982553).

FETSORN
[IBM: What is a Mainframe Simulator](https://ibmmainframes.com/about8.html).

FETSORN
[CppCyber: Desktop Cyber with Dual Mainframe/Dual CPU support](https://github.com/drsinder/CppCyber/wiki)

FETSORN
I looked for "plato mainframe cybis" on Reddit, and found that people mainly [used](https://www.reddit.com/r/mainframe/comments/jkgkev/a_mainframe_by_any_other_name_197080s_plato_iv_on/) cyber1, or [tried](https://www.reddit.com/r/EmulationOnPC/comments/ky6o87/cyber1org_vs_cybisplato_specifically_for/) to.

FETSORN
Forums led me to broken links for some of the parts of the system I would need to emulate. A [CybisRelease.zip](https://web.archive.org/web/20200113033420/http://www.control-data.info/CybisRelease.html), a DtCYBER.binaries.zip, pterm.

FETSORN
I just had to find a fresh website with links to latest releases of these, so I [searched](https://www.qwant.com/?q=download+cybisrelease1.zip&client=brz-brave&t=web) "download cybisrelease1.zip"

FETSORN
And found the control data [group](https://cdc.sjzoppi.com/doku.php?id=cybis:operation:installing
)

FETSORN
They linked to CODEX website which had all the latest [releases](https://codex.sjzoppi.com/doku.php?id=utilities:start)

FETSORN
They also had some useful [manuals](https://codex.sjzoppi.com/x-dist/cybis_operation_and_usage_manual.pdf) with instructions on how to load these emulator utilities

FETSORN
I had trouble running DtCyber on MacOS - it couldn't link libX11. First I looked for another distribution of [Desktop Cyber](https://github.com/kej715/DtCyber)

FETSORN
Then installed libx11 in a nix shell and failed to run dtcyber.

FETSORN
Then I searched for "macos libx11", stackoverflow [advised](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/46281150/how-to-install-libx11-dev-on-mac-os-x-sierra) to install [XQuartz](https://www.xquartz.org/). I remember using it a while back for wine, I think.

FETSORN
I installed it and the dtcyber script worked.

FETSORN
Then it was just like the in the CYBIS usage manual. You run dtcyber, install PLATO from the images, and login to CYBIS with an author account.

IMAGE
https://i.imgur.com/PR0dG7l.png

FETSORN
I reached the PLATO screen with lessons.

IMAGE
https://i.imgur.com/bVp4Hyc.png

FETSORN
The manual said that f9 and f10 are DATA and STOP buttons,
so I figured that f8 is BACK and f6 is HELP, or something like that
From there I went to read various HELP screens on my own.

IMAGE
https://i.imgur.com/1Co29Tf.png

FETSORN
The CYBIS manual mentioned that there were two TUTOR lessons for study mytut1 and mytut2.

IMAGE
https://i.imgur.com/vPYkLVa.png

FETSORN
I learned to edit them, debugged errors.

IMAGE
https://i.imgur.com/eIqbES4.png

FETSORN
Turned out that first 8 characters of each line were a command, and values had to be indented further.
Turned out that editing was akin to sed, you had to write i9 to edit 9th line.
This was also the time to return to "The TUTOR language" textbook to look for some code examples.

IMAGE
https://i.imgur.com/ee8iysi.png

